[4 bladen] [blad 1, recto] Ad [Addendum] Monkeys. H.W. JANSON, Apes and Ape Lore in the Middle Ages and the Renaissance (Studies of the Warburg Institute, vol. 20) London 1952, citaat p. 154 [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G.'; [blad 1, verso] citaten pp. 154, 162; [blad 2, recto-verso] citaat p. 155; [blad 3, recto] citaat p. 156 [...] (Pl. XXIIc) [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. has hardly anything to do with Bruegel: there is a bagpipe player and 4 dancing monkeys!'; [blad 3, verso] citaat p. 156 [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. But in the fable they have not sold their freedom, became captive by eating the nuts, they were badly trained, but captive.'; [blad 4, recto] citaten pp. 156-157, (Pl. XXIId) [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. Tantalus has nothing to do with Bruegel!'; [blad 4, verso] [vervolg] [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. addendum Bruegel: why 2 apes? Different attitudes! One resigned, the other still 'wilder[onleesbaar]?' Different attitudes or different stages?'[scan]
